issue(id="0008" status="open")
  title Design a same-mount dirty workspace habitat without widening trust
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer supporting modern package-manager workflows
    i-want dirtyspace to present a more natural writable workspace habitat
    so-that tools such as pnpm can use their normal same-filesystem storage behavior without forcing repo-local clutter or weakening the clean/dirty boundary
  premise.
    The current scrubs dirty runtime bind-mounts the project working tree into
    a synthetic home-based habitat. That boundary is strong and explicit, but
    it has an ergonomic side effect: some tools appear to treat the project
    tree as the natural root of their writable filesystem view.

    In practice, pnpm in `wayforge` resolves its store to `./.pnpm-store`
    rather than a user-level location, even though dirtyspace already provides
    a fake home. The likely cause is mount topology rather than a simple
    missing environment variable: the project tree and the fake home are
    separate bind mounts inside the dirty habitat, so tools that want a
    same-filesystem store fall back to a store at the root of the project
    mount.

    pnpm is the motivating case for this task today, not the only tool we
    expect might care. The intent is to solve the generic habitat problem once
    and then add other tools to the validation story as they demonstrate the
    same same-mount storage need.

    The goal is not to introduce pnpm-specific policy into scrubs base. The
    goal is to see whether scrubs can present a more natural same-mount
    writable habitat without relaxing the defensive posture around clean
    credentials, clean binaries, or unrelated writable state.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented design for a same-mount dirty workspace habitat or an explicit decision not to pursue one.
    criterion The design explains what writable paths would exist inside the habitat, how project files and scratch/user-cache space would relate to each other, and why tools like pnpm would behave more naturally there.
    criterion The design explicitly evaluates the security tradeoffs relative to the current bind-mounted dirty habitat, including credential visibility, clean binary reachability, and trusted-state contamination risks.
    criterion If a prototype is pursued, it is validated against at least one real package-manager workflow that currently tends to create repo-local state such as `.pnpm-store`.
    criterion Any chosen path keeps tool-specific policy out of neutral scrubs base unless a generic habitat design proves insufficient.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether the right primitive is an overlay-backed workspace,
      another synthetic writable root shape, or a deliberate decision to keep
      the current topology and solve specific tool issues elsewhere.
    item(status="open").
      Red-team the proposed habitat against the current boundary expectations:
      no clean credential directories, no clean `gh` or `codex`, no widened
      helper-binary reachability, and no new path for dirty workloads to
      contaminate state that cleanspace later trusts implicitly.
